sec.p:
A comparison of the content of QQ BBS and MIT BBS further exhibits that, even if censorship is not carried out by the government, webmasters and users still consciously use their own strategies to manage the forum and set up their own moderation criteria. To begin with, even at MIT BBS, keywords in the first tier are still unfavorable among users. Supporters for independence movements in Xinjiang, Tibet and Taiwan are called ‘du’; Fa lungong practitioners are called ‘lun’;
2
 democratic activists are called ‘yun’ (action). The three of them are categorized as ‘du lun yun’: the three ‘toxins’ of the forum. The two common attitudes towards posts from these three groups are either to completely ignore them by not replying to the articles or to attack them with humor. For example, Fa lungong practitioners are called ‘wheel’ (lunzi) as a soubriquet; and a famous standardized reply to them is ‘stay away from wheels, cherish your life’. The major location for ‘wheels’ is the ‘democracy salon’, which ranks 242nd of all 392 subsidiary forums. The webmaster posted the regulatory details at the top of the forum, stating that although he is against Fa lungong, he will guarantee freedom of speech for those practitioners. However, he reserves the right to remove the content. This statement was voted upon among MIT BBS users and won a majority, validating his position. Users of the forum were fed up with intrusive posts promoting the spirit of ‘wheels’ by simply slandering everything the Chinese government does without reasonable arguments or solid facts. As Awe, one of the forum participants, stated (10 July 2007 at 22:45) ‘why don’t you set up a Fa lungong salon instead? I cannot see any relation between Fa lungong and democracy. Ask your Master Li to execute his omnipotent magic and democratize China if he could’. A lot of articles were posted by ‘wheels’ on the issue of the Tian’an men Square massacre on 4 June 1989 and are critical of either the Party or government. This has triggered natural repulsion amongst users. Ge says in the interview that he constantly receives requests to evict those three groups from the forum and is given advice on tactics to fight them. Among the 234 posts about ‘4 June’, 197 were posted around its anniversary but the topic is not discussed on regular basis. Moreover, 178 posts are neutral in tone either claiming the event is more complicated than it appears to be, or acknowledging both students and government should be responsible for the consequences.
